Hull wasn't their traditional ground - people still like their 'steri', sterilised milk, whereas Beverley was a firmly fat silver-top town.

The fad for dieting led to a whole new range of skimmed milk being produced at the dairy - a reverse of the situation just a few years previously where there was no demand for milk with the cream skimmed off and it had to be fed to the pigs.

When Raymond retired, new rules which required a £2m upgrade of their dairy in Figham and falling profit margins due to customers switching to supermarket milk, were all factors in the decision to sell up.

