Quentin added: 'The customer base was disappearing rapidly, it was a change in lifestyles. People were mortgaged up and interest rates were going up and instead of the wife being at home she was going out to work.

'She didn't want the bottle on the doorstep going sour, they wanted a supermarket for convenience and it was getting cheaper.

'We were doing four pint jugs at £1.10 - it doesn't cost that much to buy 20 years on. The dairy farmers have had a raw deal I would say.'

The business ceased trading in 1992, but its memory will live on in the archives.

Sam Bartle, collections officer at East Riding Archives and Local Studies Service, said: 'As generations come and go, these archives will act as a reminder of the days of the milkman, and teach us about what was once a way of life for millions.'

